data.content:
Here are the idiomatic MSTest replacements:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0) →
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive)) →
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    foreach (var user in users)
        Assert.IsTrue(user.IsActive, $"User {user.Name} is not active");

    // Assert.IsTrue(admin != null) →
    Assert.IsNotNull(users.Single(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key MSTest assertions for collections:**

| Instead of | Use |
|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(count == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, count)` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(list.Contains(x))` | `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, x)` |
| manual equality loop | `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` (order-sensitive) |
| manual equivalence check | `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` (any order) |

**Why it matters:** `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` tells you *"expected 3 but got 5"* on failure, while `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count == 3)` just says *"expected True, got False"*.

For the `.All(u => u.IsActive)` predicate, MSTest has no built-in predicate-based collection assert — using `foreach` with a descriptive message is the idiomatic workaround.
